# Pet Circle — State Management Rules

## Architecture Overview

Pet Circle uses **global `ChangeNotifier` stores** for all shared app state. This extends the existing `ValueNotifier` pattern already used for locale and dark mode. No third-party state management packages are required.

```
lib/stores/
├── pet_store.dart            # Pet profiles
├── measurement_store.dart    # SRR measurements per pet
├── note_store.dart           # Clinical notes per pet
├── medication_store.dart     # Medications per pet
├── notification_store.dart   # In-app notifications
├── user_store.dart           # Current user and role
└── settings_store.dart       # Thresholds, preferences
```

## Store Pattern

Every store follows the same structure:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/foundation.dart';

class ExampleStore extends ChangeNotifier {
  // Private mutable state
  List<Item> _items = [];

  // Public read-only getters
  List<Item> get items => List.unmodifiable(_items);

  // Mutation methods — always call notifyListeners()
  void addItem(Item item) {
    _items.add(item);
    notifyListeners();
  }

  // Seeding from mock data
  void seed(List<Item> initial) {
    _items = List.of(initial);
    notifyListeners();
  }
}
```

### Rules

- IMPORTANT: Stores extend `ChangeNotifier`, **not** `ValueNotifier`
- IMPORTANT: All public getters return **unmodifiable** views (`List.unmodifiable`, `Map.unmodifiable`)
- IMPORTANT: Every mutation method MUST call `notifyListeners()` at the end
- State fields are private (`_items`), exposed only through getters
- Stores live in `lib/stores/`, one store per file, `snake_case.dart`
- Each store has a `seed()` method for initialization from mock data

## Global Store Instances

All stores are instantiated as top-level globals in `lib/main.dart`, matching the existing `appLocale` / `appDarkMode` pattern:

```dart
// Global store instances — seeded in main() before runApp()
final petStore = PetStore();
final measurementStore = MeasurementStore();
final noteStore = NoteStore();
final medicationStore = MedicationStore();
final notificationStore = NotificationStore();
final userStore = UserStore();
final settingsStore = SettingsStore();
```

Stores are seeded in `main()` before `runApp()`:

```dart
void main() async {
  WidgetsFlutterBinding.ensureInitialized();
  _seedStores();
  runApp(const PetCircleApp());
}

void _seedStores() {
  userStore.seed(MockData.currentOwnerUser);
  petStore.seed(
    ownerPets: MockData.hilaPets,
    clinicPets: MockData.vetClinicPets,
  );
  measurementStore.seed({
    'Princess': MockData.princessMeasurements,
  });
  noteStore.seed({
    'Princess': MockData.princessNotes,
    'Max': MockData.maxNotes,
  });
  // ... etc
}
```

## Accessing Stores in Widgets

### Reading (rebuilds on change)

Use `ListenableBuilder` to rebuild a widget subtree when a store changes:

```dart
@override
Widget build(BuildContext context) {
  return ListenableBuilder(
    listenable: petStore,
    builder: (context, _) {
      final pets = petStore.ownerPets;
      return ListView(
        children: pets.map((p) => PetCard(pet: p)).toList(),
      );
    },
  );
}
```

For multiple stores, use `Listenable.merge`:

```dart
ListenableBuilder(
  listenable: Listenable.merge([petStore, measurementStore]),
  builder: (context, _) {
    // Rebuilds when either store changes
  },
)
```

### Writing (mutations)

Call store methods directly — no context needed:

```dart
onPressed: () {
  measurementStore.addMeasurement('Princess', Measurement(
    bpm: calculatedBpm,
    recordedAt: DateTime.now(),
    recordedAtLabel: 'Just now',
  ));
}
```

### One-time reads (no rebuild)

Access store getters directly when you don't need reactive rebuilds:

```dart
final currentUser = userStore.currentUser;
final notes = noteStore.getNotes('Princess');
```

## Import Convention

```dart
// Import the store file — the global instance is the top-level variable
import 'package:pet_circle/stores/pet_store.dart';
import 'package:pet_circle/stores/measurement_store.dart';
```

The global instance (e.g. `petStore`) is exported from the store file itself, NOT from `main.dart`.

## Store Registry

| Store | Global | State | Key Methods |
|-------|--------|-------|-------------|
| `PetStore` | `petStore` | Owner pets, clinic pets | `addPet`, `updatePet`, `removePet`, `getPetByName` |
| `MeasurementStore` | `measurementStore` | Measurements per pet | `addMeasurement`, `getMeasurements`, `latestForPet` |
| `NoteStore` | `noteStore` | Clinical notes per pet | `addNote`, `getNotes` |
| `MedicationStore` | `medicationStore` | Medications per pet | `addMedication`, `removeMedication`, `getMedications` |
| `NotificationStore` | `notificationStore` | App notifications | `addNotification`, `markRead`, `markAllRead` |
| `UserStore` | `userStore` | Current user + role | `setUser`, `setRole` |
| `SettingsStore` | `settingsStore` | Thresholds, prefs | `updateThresholds`, toggle methods |

## Migration Path (from MockData to Stores)

When updating a screen to use stores:

1. Replace `MockData.xxx` imports with the appropriate store import
2. Wrap data-dependent UI in `ListenableBuilder(listenable: xxxStore, ...)`
3. Replace direct `MockData` references with store getters
4. Replace local `setState` mutations with store method calls
5. Remove any local state that duplicates store state

Example — before:
```dart
import 'package:pet_circle/data/mock_data.dart';
// ...
final pets = MockData.hilaPets;
```

After:
```dart
import 'package:pet_circle/stores/pet_store.dart';
// ...
ListenableBuilder(
  listenable: petStore,
  builder: (context, _) {
    final pets = petStore.ownerPets;
    // ...
  },
)
```

## Data Flow Diagram

```
MockData (seed) ──► Stores (ChangeNotifier) ──► Screens (ListenableBuilder)
                         ▲                            │
                         │                            │
                         └──── User Actions ──────────┘
                              (store.method())
```

## Future: Firebase Migration

When `kEnableFirebase` is set to `true`, stores will be updated to:
1. Load initial data from Firestore instead of MockData
2. Write mutations to Firestore, then update local state
3. Listen to Firestore streams for real-time sync

The screen-facing API (getters, methods) will NOT change — only the store internals.
